GIT-INJECT(1)                     Git Manual                      GIT-INJECT(1)

NAME
       git-inject - Merge a newer commit into an older commit

SYNOPSIS
       git inject <target> [<patch>] [--copy] [--branch <branch>]
       git inject [-w | --working-tree] <target> [--branch <branch>]
       git inject (--continue | --abort | --revert | --clear)

INSTALLATION
       Clone the repository and then run the installation script for your
       operating system.

       Windows:

           powershell.exe -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\install.ps1

       Linux/macOS:

           chmod +x install.sh
           ./install.sh

MODE OPTIONS
       --continue
              Resume the injection process after resolving merge conflicts.
              Use this instead of native git continue commands.

       --abort
              Abort the inject operation and reset HEAD to the original
              branch and restores any stashed changes. Use this instead of
              native git abort commands.

       --revert
              Reset HEAD to the original branch and exact state prior to the
              last successful or failed injection. This process can only be
              done once and for the most recent injection.

              This action will not recover uncommitted changes before the
              injection when using git inject --working-tree.

       --clear
              Clean up the git-inject working files (see FILES below).

              If an injection is manually aborted using native git commands
              (e.g., git rebase --abort) outside of git-inject, this may
              leave behind state tracking files.

OPTIONS
       <target>
              The older commit that receives the changes. This commit must
              be a direct ancestor of the <patch> commit.

       <patch>
              The newer commit containing the changes to merge. This
              commit is removed from the branch history during injection.

       -w
       --working-tree
              Inject all changes in the working tree into the specified
              target. These are uncommitted changes and will not return to
              the staging area when git inject --revert is used.

              See also INCOMPATIBLE OPTIONS below.

       --into <target>
              Syntactic sugar. Inject the current HEAD commit into the
              specified target. Does not alter script operation.

       --copy
              Copy diff changes from one commit to another. Commits copied
              are not deleted.

              See also INCOMPATIBLE OPTIONS and BUGS below.

       --branch <branch>
              Perform the injection on the specified branch instead of the
              current one.

              See also BUGS below.

       --theirs
              Resolve merge conflicts by favoring the changes from the
              newer patch commit. This applies to internal rebase and
              cherry-pick operations.

              If you expect conflicts and want the newer patch commit's
              changes to automatically overwrite the older target's changes,
              you can pass the --theirs flag. This applies the '-X theirs'
              merge strategy and bypasses manual conflict resolution for
              those files.

INCOMPATIBLE OPTIONS
       The following pairs of options are incompatible:

       --working-tree and --copy
       --working-tree and <patch>

EXAMPLES
       Merge the current HEAD into an older commit:

              git inject f1a2b3
              git inject --into f1a2b3
              git inject HEAD~3

       Merge a specific commit into an older commit:

              git inject abc1234 def5678
              git inject HEAD~7 HEAD^

       Inject a patch into a different branch:

              git inject --branch develop f1a2b3 h7i8j9

       Merge a missing file and automatically resolve conflicts in favor
       of the patch:

              git inject f1a2b3 h7i8j9 --theirs

       Inject all changes in the working tree into an older commit:

              git inject -w
              git inject -w f1a2b3

BUGS
       If --branch is specified and the patch commit is older than the target
       commit, the injection will proceed without error.

       When reverting an injection which used --copy, git-inject does not
       remember where the commit was copied from which results in a broken
       tree.

SANDBOX
       To create a temporary sandbox to test the command, download the
       repository then run

           chmod +x ./test/sandbox
           ./test/sandbox setup

       and navigate to the generated 'git-inject-sandbox/' folder and open
       the git project.

       The sandbox is crated with six branches, two of which are orphan
       branches and the other four are split between the orphans, two each.
       The included files are designed to be distinguishable from each other
       by file extension.

       Here's what the branch tree structure would look like:

           * 82f1807 (feature)           * 6cf071b (reference)
           | * 6c0b3b1 (topic)           | * 41d729a (article)
           | | * b4afe1c (master)        | | * 6316505 (docs)
           | |/                          | |/
           |/|                           |/|
           * | d08a371                   * | 02a7b8f
           |/                            |/
           * 34252d6                     * b6d343a

       The tree is truncated to cut down unnecessary empty space.

AUTHOR
